        <paragraph>A MultiplayerPeer implementation using the <reference name="ENet" refuri="http://enet.bespin.org/index.html">ENet</reference> library.</paragraph>
        <section classes="classref-introduction-group" ids="description" names="description">
            <title>Description</title>
            <paragraph>A MultiplayerPeer implementation that should be passed to <reference internal="True" refuri="class_multiplayerapi#class-multiplayerapi-property-multiplayer-peer"><inline classes="std std-ref">MultiplayerAPI.multiplayer_peer</inline></reference> after being initialized as either a client, server, or mesh. Events can then be handled by connecting to <reference internal="True" refuri="class_multiplayerapi#class-multiplayerapi"><inline classes="std std-ref">MultiplayerAPI</inline></reference> signals. See <reference internal="True" refuri="class_enetconnection#class-enetconnection"><inline classes="std std-ref">ENetConnection</inline></reference> for more information on the ENet library wrapper.</paragraph>
            <paragraph><strong>Note:</strong> ENet only uses UDP, not TCP. When forwarding the server port to make your server accessible on the public Internet, you only need to forward the server port in UDP. You can use the <reference internal="True" refuri="class_upnp#class-upnp"><inline classes="std std-ref">UPNP</inline></reference> class to try to forward the server port automatically when starting the server.</paragraph>
